If you were to somehow personify hospitality, I'm certain that those avatars would look a lot like the guys at Snail Thai.  I've been visiting this restaurant for about two years now, and each time I go I am greeted with warm recognition. It feels like returning to old friends.  The food is always freshly prepared and delicious. I always go with the fried shrimp and the pot stickers for appetizers. Then, I follow that up with the ginger chicken, the bird's nest noodles, or the fried rice (because I like a good cliché every now and then).  There are two other Thai food places located along Garfield Blvd, I'm told, but as far as I'm concerned Snail Thai is the only one that exists.

They are local, super friendly and accommodating, and we noticed there were regular customers who sat down and didn't even have to order. The waiter already knew what they wanted. Service was attentive.  The appetizers (shumai and suan tong) came out quickly and with plenty of time for us to finish before the meal.  The suan tong fried vegetables were just the right size for balancing crisp exterior with the interior - batter stayed on instead of falling off.  They were good without the sweet dipping sauce, though it did elevate the experience.. I had pad Thai and asked for shrimp AND tofu because I could not choose one.  It was a little on the wet side but the flavor was good, if sweet.  I am used to being given limes and extra peanuts but I didn't care enough to inquire.  My child liked the waitress's recommendation of pad see ew - wheat noodles in a sweet sauce with broccoli florets.  The wide noodles were tasty but a little foreign looking for the little one.  She eventually grew to like them.  My partner loved the drunken noodles.

The restaurant is a bit small but the food is delicious. I ordered the padkimao which was supposed to "be a spicier take on pad see ew" but I was disappointed that it was barely spicy. They accommodated for my food allergies and the service was great.

Then, the next time I came in, she sat down with me so we could calculate the calories.  And I'm so happy because omigawd I don't know how I went without the red curry for so long.

I usually eat ate another Thai restaurant down the same road but was asked to try something new and boy Snail does not disappoint. At first I was thrown off by the side of the restaurant they sat my friend and I. It was mostly decorated in a southwestern motif and Mexican music was playing over their speakers. They even left a bowl of tortilla chips on the table(?). We were a little confused until they brought the menus to the table. Not a Mexican dish in sight so we knew we were in the right place. Rest assured, the other side of the restaurant is decorated like a more traditional Thai restaurant.  Now I judge my Thai restaurants by the quality of three food items. The iced coffee, the satay and the broccoli chicken.  I'm part Thai so I'm a tough sell on these items since I'm impartial to my mothers cooking. The iced coffee was superb, it was just the right amount of sweet and not doused with tons of cream. The chicken satay was cooked perfectly and had just the right amount of peanut sauce.  The broccoli chicken I ordered had tender chicken and crispy broccoli which is exactly the way I like it.  We went during lunch rush and even thou it was busy we frequently saw our waitress and they were very attentive. I will be back again and would recommend others to give it a try.

I am writing a review on this place first time and had ordered delivery.  Thus I cannot comment on the decor since I've never seen this place and only found through google.  I used their online ordering which was really easy and user-friendly.  It stated 45-60 minutes to deliver, but it arrived in shorter time.  The driver was very kind.  I order the Golden Bag (sweet corns, peas and potatos) which was very crisp and crunchy.  The top part I didn't eat since I don't like the fried part, but the bottom filling was really good and soft with an outer crunch.  Also, ordered ginger noodles noodles (fresh ginger, chili sauce, onion, peapods, carrots and chinese cabbage) including red bell peppers and baby corns tho not listed which was fine with me.  It was delicious, taste the ginger, and amazing fresh chili sauce, and the thin noodles was really good. Lastly, of course included dessert, a sweet taro root with ginko nuts with sticky rice.....ohmygod.....delicious, unique, and sweet. But you need to have a taste for it especially for sweet foods (not chocolate sweet type). I will definitely order again and try another veg dish on the menu and I recommend this to anyone who want to explore Hyde Park.
